Here's the recommended approach using **Window lifecycle events** and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
```

### Key points

- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background; restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **`Preferences`** is fast and synchronous — ideal for small values like draft text. Keep handlers under 1–2 seconds to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS.
- **`OnResumed` does NOT fire on first launch** — the initial sequence is `Created → Activated`. Load any persisted draft in your page's constructor or `OnAppearing` for the cold-start case.
